posts.name: stu54
posts.cooked: I am new to object detection and working in a Linux environment on my local machine. I followed the steps in the YOLOv8 Training and Conversion to RKNN - Team 5990 TRIGON collab notebook, translating it into a local Python environment using the Cones-and-Cubes dataset. After training my model, I can verify its performance using the model(images).results.show(), which displays bounding boxes around cubes on my monitor with high confidence. I converted and quantized the trained model for i8 and exported it to RKNN. However, my Orange Pi 5 Pro isn't recognizing the cubes despite adjusting LifeCam settings and experimenting with area/ratio sliders. There's no debug output from Photonvision to identify if the uploaded model is being used correctly. I'm unsure how to move forward to get a functional model.

posts.name: Sam
posts.cooked: Ensure the uploaded model was trained on images matching the pipeline’s resolution. Verify that the model is correctly named and has been selected in the pipeline.

posts.name: stu54
posts.cooked: I trained on 640×640 images but cannot set my camera resolution to 640×640—it’s not an option on the Photonvision camera settings. My closest option is 640×480. Can I enter any value instead of the dropdown choices?

posts.name: Sam
posts.cooked: 640x480 is the resolution you would want. Please test whether the model included with the image is functioning.

posts.name: stu54
posts.cooked: I will obtain an algae specimen from our robotics lab and attempt it at home the next day. Previously, when I utilized my own captured images instead of the Trigon dataset and uploaded them to RoboFlow, I conducted a post-processing step to resize them to 640x640 pixels. However, this adjustment resulted in image distortion due to loss of aspect ratio. Should this be a concern? Additionally, do you know of a functional model and suitable dataset for PhotonVision that incorporates typical game components such as rings, cones, or cubes?

posts.name: stu54
posts.cooked: When I tested the system using the built-in algae model, it functioned properly. Subsequently, I deployed my trained YOLOv5n model on the OrangePi via the rknn_model_zoo Python example script, successfully detecting orange rings and a tennis ball within a 640x640 JPEG image captured from the same webcam. I now seek to understand how PhotonVision might be utilizing my model differently compared to the approach taken by Rockchip-based solutions.

posts.name: Sam
posts.cooked: Is your model quantized using the RKNN format? Did you convert it first before quantizing? I believe that can have an effect as well.

posts.name: Yishai Levy
posts.cooked:
What was the mAP50 on your best train? For how long did you train? What’s the confidence threshold? For how long did you train the model?

Honestly, I don’t remember if we ever used or tested the cones and cubes dataset. We mostly used our notes dataset from 2024, and this year we’ve used the coral and algae dataset.

posts.name: stu54
posts.cooked:
In the rknn_model_zoo (on the OrangePi using my own Ubuntu 22.04.5 LTS install) I used this to convert:

python convert.py best.onnx rk3588 i8 yolo5n.rknn

I used this to run the test:

python yolov5.py --model_path yolo5n.rknn --target rk3588 --img_folder /home/orange/pi/yolo/images --img_save

Here is the result image. I think the labels are coming from the COCO dataset and the anchors are from the rknn_model_zoo directory, as loaded by the yolov5.py script. I don’t know if the default anchors would have any effect when it comes to PhotonVision. I don’t really understand the concept of anchors and role they play. Also, I should mention that I trained with very few images but an epoch of 500 because I just want to see if I can get everything right to try my model in PhotonVision. The original Ultralytics model was yolov5s.yaml but here I renamed it yolo5n. Not sure if the naming would matter.

This is the result image.

posts.name: Sam
posts.cooked: Yes, that naming matters. It's important to use the right code for the version you're using. You've been switching between v5 and v8 based on your posts, and Rknn_model_zoo offers different codes for various versions.

posts.name: stu54
posts.cooked: Retraining on the V5 model allowed me to explore whether an alternative version might perform better. By lowering the confidence threshold, PhotonVision began recognizing objects, though this led to numerous false identifications within the scene. I now need to investigate why the confidence levels in PhotonVision are considerably lower than those shown in my recent post using the model zoo Python script. How do PhotonVision's interactions differ from the RockChip model zoo example? Previously, I tested my model using the YOLOv5 model zoo before integrating it into PhotonVision.

posts.name: Sam
posts.cooked: PV shouldn't treat the model any differently. If the model is quantized incorrectly, however, that can sometimes lead to confidence values being off. Can you try and quantize the model again?

posts.name: stu54
posts.cooked: ok so i got my model to work with training a yolo11n model. there was an extra step required using the ultralytics_yolo11 repository from airockchip. that step simplifies the custom trained yolo11n.pt model coming out of ultralytics and creates the onnx version. then when the model is converted to rknn using the rknn_model_zoo it works in photonvision.
